What do you mean by proper wiring?



----- Original Message ----
From: &quot;Marlboro63@...&quot; &lt;Marlboro63@...&gt;
To: EVP-ITC@yahoogroups.com
Sent: Wednesday, August 13, 2008 1:29:36 PM
Subject: Re: [EVP-ITC] Speakers


Those speakers should work for what you want to do.  But you could 
also get the proper wiring and run directly into the recorder at the same 
time.  The choice is up to you.

In a message dated 8/13/2008 12:25:19 P.M. Central Daylight Time, 
cawiggins78@ yahoo.com writes:
I went over to BigLots and got a set of Audio Zone 2.0 amplified speakers  for about 6 bucks. They are 2W each with a 3&quot; full range driver, pre-amplified  and magnetically shielded. Frequency response is 120Hz-20KHz. Are these just  total crap, or are they comparable to what you&#39;re talking about? Man, I just  wish I could run the mic and the 469 into the recorder with the  y-adapter.



-----  Original Message ----
From: &quot;Marlboro63@ aol.com&quot;  &lt;Marlboro63@aol. com&gt;
To: EVP-ITC@yahoogroups .com
Sent:  Wednesday, August 13, 2008 1:08:32 PM
Subject: Re: [EVP-ITC]  Speakers


The 469 uses a very low powered amplifier circuit on the headphone  jack.  Stand computer speakers will not really work for it and you will  get a very low audio out of it if anything.  What you need is a small set  of amplified speakers.  Radio Shack sells a few seats that fold up for  around $20.00.  I got mine when they were on sale for $10.00.  Or  any good amplified speakers will do the job for you.  But remember the  clocking on am.  The clicking will be amplified too so try and ignore it  if possible.

Jeff

In a message dated 8/13/2008 12:05:35 P.M. Central Daylight Time,  cawiggins78@ yahoo.com writes:
I hooked up these speakers and now I&#39;m not getting a thing. I  guess
I&#39;m using poor quality speakers. any suggestions on which  speakers
work the best with the 469?






